Dioscorea opposita

   [5408.jpg]
    Authority   Thunb.
      Family    Liliopsida:Liliidae:Dioscoreales:Dioscoreaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 5408

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A woody plant with spineless stems climbing to a
   height of 3 m. The leaves are 4-8 cm in length. The tubers are club or
   spindle-shaped, up to 1 m in length, growing in a vertical direction.
   USES The underground tubers are cooked like potatoes, often after
   slicing or grating and boiling. The plant is often grown as an
   ornamental but escapes easily and can be come a weed in waste areas.
   GROWING PERIOD Perennial vine, tubers may be harvested 160-180 days
   from sowing. COMMON NAMES Chinese yam, Chinese potato, Cinnamon vine,
   Igname de Chine, Name de Chino. FURTHER INF Scientific synonym: D.
   batatas. Chinese yam is native of China. Optimum daylengths for both
   tuber and bulbil formation are 10-11 hours. Yields may be in the region
   of 4-6 t/ha.

   Sources
   SOURCES (Dioscorea opposita Thunb.)
   Tindall H 1983 pp 201-202 & 216 [TEMP, RAIN, PHO, TEXT, FER]
   Duke J 1975 pp 15 (D. oppositifolia) [PH, RAIN, TEMP]
   Roecklein J 1987 pp 464 [USE]
   Purseglove J 1972 pp 107 [USE]

